title: ‚ÄúThe LGBTQIA+ movement is stronger now than ever before.‚Äù How do you CARE WITH PRIDE¬Æ?
‚ÄúCertain people in the LGBTQIA+ community are given more of a voice than others.‚Äù
‚ÄúIt was difficult for me to come out.‚Äù How do you CARE WITH PRIDE¬Æ in YOUR community?
What Was It Like To Come Out? | LGBTQ+ Leaders
description:
How do you CARE WITH PRIDE¬Æ in YOUR community? Hear from a diverse set of LGBTQIA+ leaders about their personal and professional journeys striving for social justice, equality and a sense of true belonging for all in this special Spectrum episode that asks the question: do all LGBTQIA+ people think the same?

Join leaders from diverse LGBTQIA+ nonprofits Family Equality, OutRight International, The LGBT+ Center Orlando, The Newark Center, Okra Project, and Trans Chorus of LA to discuss what makes us tick as queer humans, as a global community and as an active civil rights movement. CARE WITH PRIDE¬Æ is proud to uplift marginalized voices by passing the mic to those whose voices deserve to be heard. Visit carewithpride.com to learn more about the initiative‚Äôs continued commitment to supporting the LGBTQIA+ community.

description: Police brutality; is it a thing in Japan? Black residents discuss their experiences with the Japanese police. #SpectrumBeingBlackIn #Japan #Jubilee

title: What Is It Like To Be Black In Japan?  | SPECTRUM: Being Black in‚Ä¶Asia
description:
SPECTRUM is taking over the world and exploring the Black experience one continent at a time. In this first episode of our three-part special we visit Japan. Natives and expats gather on our SPECTRUM stage to candidly discuss sexuality, dating, dealing with police, fitting into the community and how difficult it is to get your hair done. Their conversation offers an intimate look at life in a country with a completely different culture from the West but one that shares similar pressures.

title: Recipe for Change: Standing Up to Antisemitism with Idina Menzel, Ilana Glazer & Moshe Kasher
description:
Dinner, Discussions & Jewish identity. 
 
In ‚ÄúRecipe for Change: Standing Up to Antisemitism,‚Äù hosts Idina Menzel, Ilana Glazer & Moshe Kasher are joined by Skylar Astin, Michael Ian Black, Rachel Bloom, Rabbi Sharon Brous, Tommy Dorfman, Alex Edelman, Hannah Einbinder, Jordan Firstman, Lori Gottlieb, Bryan Greenberg, ADL CEO Jonathan Greenblatt, Hari Nef, Josh Peck, Zac Posen, Ruth Reichl, Rachel Sumekh, and Michael Zegen for some amazing meals and timely chat. Together they celebrate their Jewish heritage, identity, & culture, and discuss the rise of antisemitism and its effects on the Jewish community. While they engage in their discourse, they also dine on delicious dinners prepared by esteemed chefs Nancy Silverton and Einat Admony, and culinary historian Michael Twitty. Rachel Dratch also joins the special episode as an on-the-street reporter, speaking with Jewish people and allies in New York City.
Don‚Äôt just take a seat at the table; take a stand.

For every face mask purchased at https://www.humangoodla.com/collections/surface-level/products/humangood-facemask, we'll donate a medical-grade mask to a local hospital. Want to learn from and create with us for 2 weeks this August? APPLY for Jubilee Fellowship 2018. Applications due May 20: http://jubileemedia.com/fellowship

What happens when you mix an urban art form like hip hop and a classical genre like opera? Time to find out. We brought together a producer who has worked with some of the biggest names in hip hop and a massively accomplished opera singer to see if music transcends genre & style.

title: 3 Buff Men Share Their Feelings With Each Other
description:
"Life is all about love. It's okay for a man to have affection and show affection. It doesn't make him weak at all."

In 1997, a psychologist conducted an experiment that could lead any two people to fall in love with just 36 questions. We wanted to see what would happen if we brought 3 complete strangers together to answer those questions together. In this episode, 3 men defy conventional stereotypes by opening up and being vulnerable with each other.

title: Can Strangers Love Each Other In 36 Questions?
description:
"You completely broke all my expectations - how intimate your stories are. Honestly, I think it's really courageous and I think you're beautiful."

In 1997, a psychologist conducted an experiment that could lead any two people to fall in love with just 36 questions. We wanted to see what would happen if we brought 3 complete strangers together to answer those questions together. In this episode, 3 women from different backgrounds see if they can experience love, intimacy, and closeness with people they've just met.

title: Save My Seoul - Official Trailer
description:
Pre-order on iTunes: http://bit.ly/savemyseoulfilm

SAVE MY SEOUL is a Jubilee Media original documentary that unveils South Korea‚Äôs rampant prostitution and sex-trafficking secret and the young women it exploits. 

Film releases via iTunes on July 4th.

| SYNOPSIS |
Eddie and Jason, two Korean-American brothers get in over their heads when they are called to Korea to make a short film on prostitution and sex-trafficking. Things get complicated when they meet Crystal and Esther, two prostitutes who reveal just how deep the problem goes and set off on a dangerous mission to capture the truth.

With the use of hidden cameras and access to pimps, johns, and sex-workers, the filmmakers explore and unravel the complexity of the sex trade in Seoul. They learn that this problem is rooted in issues far deeper than exploited girls and lustful men. Instead, it's a consequence of a culture and government that turns a blind eye to and condones the biggest human injustice of our time.

www.savemyseoul.com

title: Muslim Parents' Open Letter to Their Children
description:
Like us on Facebook! http://facebook.com/jubileemedia

In a time of much division, fear, and hate, "Dear Child" is a video series that seeks to remind us of our shared humanity. We invited Muslim parents to share a message to their children about their racial and religious identity, and how to respond to prejudice and Islamophobia they may experience. We hope that one day, Muslim parents will no longer have to have this talk with their children, but until then we hope their message will awaken us to this reality they currently face and inspire understanding.

Other videos in the Dear Child series include:
Black Parents have "The Talk" with their Children https://youtu.be/Mkw1CetjWwI

Jubilee Project is a digital media company that hopes to tell stories that inspire change.

title: Dear Child - When Black Parents Have To Give "The Talk"
description:
Like us on Facebook! http://facebook.com/jubileemedia

WHY WE MADE DEAR CHILD:
Jubilee Project is a digital media company that tells stories to explore our humanity. It has been heartbreaking and infuriating to witness the senseless and unjust killings of black men in the United States. And we'd like to play our part in addressing this epidemic through the creation of ‚ÄúDear Child.‚Äù We hope that by sharing some of these candid responses from black parents and young adults, we can inspire understanding and empathy from those who have never needed to have such a talk. 

We know that a video cannot be the solution or panacea and that there is so much complexity we do not even begin to confront. However, we do believe this is one way to ignite compassion and dialogue.

Sincerely,
Jason
Director, Dear Child

title: World Without Teachers
description:
Like us on Facebook! http://facebook.com/jubileemedia

This Teacher Appreciation Month, we want to honor the teachers around the world. They not only taught us the fundamentals of our education - reading, writing, mathematics - but also became our role models and inspiration for life. It's no doubt that teachers have had a profound impact on our lives. This month, as students are graduating and finishing up the school year, Jubilee Project is proud to share with you "World Without Teachers" a short video that takes a moment to look back on the teachers in our lives and how they have shaped who we are.

Everybody knows that teachers make a huge difference in our lives. Yet less than 10% of top-tier undergrads express any interest in teaching as a career. Without more young people going into the field of education, it is a real possibility that some children will grow up without the impactful influence of great teachers in their lives.

Jubilee Project is proud to partner with Participant Media's TEACH campaign to encourage passionate, creative, innovative young people to consider teaching as a career. Together, let's help build a world where every student has a great teacher to guide them along the way. 

*Special thanks to everybody to shared their stories with us.* 

| #BeATeacher CAMPAIGN |

1.) TWEET US - In 140 characters or less tell us why it is important to #BeATeacher.  Tell us how they have impacted your life and how they have inspired you! Click here to tweet --- http://ctt.ec/b1NDE

2.) PLEDGE - Join the TEACH campaign at http://www.TakePart.com/TEACH and Take The TEACH Pledge at http://bit.ly/TEACHPledge2

3.) WATCH MORE - We created a playlist of inspiring videos about teaching. Watch them to be inspired and learn more about teachers: http://bit.ly/1F41iMm

title: World Without Black People
description:
Tweet: http://ctt.ec/5i3c7 | Facebook: http://on.fb.me/1xLYE99
Like us on Facebook! http://facebook.com/jubileemedia

These days it can be so hard to talk about race and racism. It's taboo, polarizing, and nuanced. But it is also one of the most important topics of our generation. So we went to the streets to have a conversation about it. From Boston to LA, we heard stories that were raw and honest. This Martin Luther King, Jr. Day, we are proud to share with you "World Without Black People", a glimpse into the conversation that we had about race and what it is like to be a black person living in America. We made this video to share these stories, stand in solidarity with our black brothers and sisters, and challenge you to have a similar conversation of your own. We made this video because #BlackLivesMatter.

Read a letter from the director here: http://jubileeproject.org/?p=4137

| #WeCanDoBetterBy CAMPAIGN |
"Get to know somebody that doesn't look like you, worship next to somebody who doesn't look like you, share a meal with somebody who doesn't look like you and come with no expectations...then you'll see who we are." If you are watching this video, this is your call to action. We want you to join us in our #WeCanDoBetterBy Campaign:

1.) TWEET US -  In 140 characters or less, tell us what you can do to break down racial stereotypes and inspire others to do the same. Finish the sentence: #WeCanDoBetterBy....., and don‚Äôt forget to tag @JubileeProject. You can use this link: http://ctt.ec/QCqsU

2.) WATCH VIDEOS - We put together a short playlist of some of our favorite videos about race / racism. They have facts and practical advice on how we can do better. Check them out: http://bit.ly/1xn8j78

3.) TAKE ACTION - Meet up with a friend who is a different race than you and have a conversation about personal experiences of racism. Keep an open mind and loving heart. Break away from stereotypes of what it means to be a certain race. You never know what you'll learn.

title: Join Us! | Jubilee Project 2014 Fundraiser
description:
Tweet: http://ctt.ec/P6HtE | Support us here: http://jubileeproject2014.causevox.com/

Hey guys! It's been an incredible four years working on Jubilee Project. From our very first videos back in 2010 to today, we've learned and grown so much. We hope that you have enjoyed watching our videos!

You guys have been such amazing supporters of our work over the past four years. We wouldn't be here without you. We don't usually do this, but we want to take a moment to ask you to consider supporting Jubilee Project financially. The truth is that while the majority of our funding comes from sponsorships, grants, events, and merch, we also depend on donations to continue to do our work. 

This year, our goal is to raise $40,000 by December 31st, 2014 (that's in 40 days!). This is our #40x40project. Your donation would go directly to new original short films, documentaries (like Save My Seoul), and to fund our summer film fellowship and annual conference. 

| HOW CAN I SUPPORT THE CAMPAIGN? |
The easiest way is to make a direct donation on our fundraising page. Whether it is $5 or $500, every bit counts and we are so appreciative of your support.

You can also make a sustaining donation. A sustaining donation is a monthly donation that helps us continue our work. Your donation is processed automatically each month and you can cancel at any time.

| HOW CAN I DO MORE? |
You can also create your own fundraising campaign page and invite your friends to join in! Get creative with fundraising! You can host an event, run a race, donate your holiday gifts and more. With the help of friends and family, we can raise more together!

| I CANNOT GIVE FINANCIALLY RIGHT NOW, IS THERE ANYTHING I CAN DO? |
The easiest way is to spread the word to your friends and family. Share with them about what Jubilee Project does and how it has impacted your life. That is one of the best ways that you can support us!

| FAQ |
Jubilee Project is a registered 501(c)3 nonprofit organization. All donations are tax-deductible. You will receive an emailed tax receipt via email.

If you are interested in giving a major gift or a gift via check, please email us directly at project.jubilee@gmail.com.

title: Save My Seoul - 2014 Trailer
description:
Tweet: http://ctt.ec/bF595 | Official Website: http://www.savemyseoul.com

Jubilee Project is proud to share the official trailer to our feature-length documentary film, Save My Seoul. 

Save My Seoul follows two Korean-American brothers as they discover rampant prostitution and sex trafficking in Seoul, South Korea. With the use of hidden cameras and access to pimps, johns, and sex-workers, Eddie and Jason explore and unravel the complexity of the sex trade in Seoul. They learn that this problem is rooted in issues far deeper than lost girls and lustful men. Instead, it's a consequence of the broken Korean culture that turns a blind eye to and condones one of the biggest human injustices of our generation. 

The purpose of Save My Seoul is to raise awareness of prostitution and sex trafficking in Korea for the Western world and ultimately to spur action to end trafficking in Korea and beyond. Because local Koreans are so familiar with this issue, we believe that change will happen when the world becomes aware of this brokenness in Korea. And it begins by shining a light on these injustices. 

Full documentary will be released in Spring 2015. Subscribe to Jubilee Project and follow Save My Seoul on social media for more information about how to get involved.

description:
Tweet: http://ctt.ec/evoF4 | Facebook: http://on.fb.me/1qiakhY

In June of 2014, Jubilee Project hosted its second fellowship program inviting 11 filmmakers to live together and produce a short film. They produced 3 short films to challenge others to live for something greater. Learn more about the fellowship here: http://www.jubileeproject.org/fellowship

‚ÄúExposure‚Äù follows the journey of an aspiring photographer whose life is changed when she finds an unexpected surprise while given the opportunity to give a eulogy for her father who recently passed away.

Through this short film, we want to encourage you to take the opportunities given to you before they are gone. Whether it‚Äôs the opportunity to chase your dreams, or tell someone you love them, opportunities are given to  us to pursue. Our main character took the opportunity to chase after her passion in photography, yet failed to remember the importance of telling her father she loved him. Our hope is for no one to have that regret of what could have been.  We encourage you, as well as anyone who watches ‚ÄúExposure,‚Äù to not miss the chances given. 

| TAKE ACTION |
We believe that opportunities are given for us to pursue.  Are there any opportunities that you want to take a shot at?  Take our #JPEXPOSURE 30 day challenge! 

We'd love for you to share the opportunities in your life with us and the rest of the JP community. Using the set of lists below and share something each day for 30 days on social media: Twitter, Facebook, or Instagram - it's up to you - just make sure you use the #JPExposure hashtag! Together, let's commit 30 days to taking hold of our opportunities.

description:

In June of 2014, Jubilee Project hosted its second fellowship program inviting 11 filmmakers to live together and produce a short film in 2 weeks. They produced 3 short films to challenge others to live for something greater. Learn more about the fellowship here: http://www.jubileeproject.org/fellowship

Sometimes, even the most honorable goals can blind us from our own needs. And sometimes, it's easy to feel trapped by the fear of not being good enough. As Austin, a varsity swimmer, works towards his dream goal in life, he spirals into a cycle of self-harm and develops eating disordered behavior. With the help of his friend Chase, Austin is able to confront his dark secret, embrace imperfection, and begin to live for something greater.

Inspired by, and in honor of, those who struggle with or have overcome eating disorders or mental illness. We believe everyone is meant for a great purpose that cannot be measured by achievements. #LiveForSomethingGreater #JPYouAreMore

title: This Is Your Invitation | Jubilee Project Fellowship 2014
description:
Tweet: http://ctt.ec/Vsp26 | Apply: http://www.jubileeproject.org/fellowship

During the summer of 2014, Jubilee Project (www.jubileeproject.org) will be offering a 12-day summer fellowship in Los Angeles, CA for filmmakers & creatives on June 9th-21st. Jubilee Project will select between 6-12 young aspiring filmmakers (ages 18+) to live in a community house to work & create impactful films together. The fellowship aims to bring together talented creatives who are passionate about creating films by collaborating and learning from each other, the JP team & other guests/friends of Jubilee Project. Applications are due March 24th, 2014 - for any questions please email: project.jubilee (at) gmail.com.

description:
Tweet: http://clicktotweet.com/b9pE7 | FB: http://on.fb.me/1g4zBuW

This is the story of how three boys left consulting, the White House, and Harvard Medical School to pursue the dream of changing the world. 

But we didn't realize was that the world was going to change us. 

We had an opportunity this spring to travel to Indonesia with our friend Kate and meet Ginan, founder of Rumah Cemara, and a little boy named Fijar. We learned more about the devastating effects of HIV/AIDS, from the daily struggles to the death toll to the stigma and discrimination HIV positive people face. 

But for everything that this virus has done to destroy, it has also brought incredible strength and resilience, commitment and love, community and hope. Together, we can defeat HIV and end AIDS in our generation.

title: Melody | Jubilee Project Film
description:
This is a story about love. 
Tweet: http://bit.ly/1aj9Wsj | FB: http://on.fb.me/1fvH1oL
Clothing Sponsor: http://www.yesstyle.com 

After finding out that he will soon lose his memories, an elderly breakdancer is determined to protect the last memory he will have with his little granddaughter. 

Inspired by Eric's relationship with his grandfather, this film raises awareness for Alzheimer's Disease. This is a condition that causes loss of brain function affecting memory, thinking, and behavior. Alzheimer's is most common in people ages 65 and older, but some get it in their 40s and 50s. 

We made this film to show that even though people with Alzheimer's may no longer seem like themselves, they still need the love that can make a difference in their lives. The disease strips people of their capacity for memories, but it doesn't strip away their capacity for love and companionship. In the end, emotions outlast memories. 

| WRITE US |
What's your favorite memory? Share your response by tweeting us @jubileeproject with #livewhatyoulove. We'll pick one winner by October 23, 2013 to receive a new t-shirt we're designing called "Live What You Love".

title: Alstroemeria: A Jubilee Project Fellowship Short Film
description:
This summer, Jubilee Project hosted a fellowship program inviting 13 filmmakers to live together and produce a short film in 10 days. They produced three short films that inspire change. This is Alstroemeria. Learn more about the fellowship here: www.jubileeproject.org/fellowship

How do you stand up by sitting down? Our short film asks one simple question: Can you stand up for someone by simply sitting down beside them?

We often don't think about how our words can hurt others. Adolescents and young adults in the LGBT community often find themselves on the receiving end of harmful comments and malicious hate, and have one of the highest suicide attempt rates in the country. They often face the internal struggle of discovering who they are, as well as the external pressure of fitting into majority norms.

We believe that acts of kindness generated out of love are an important way to build each other up. Sometimes something as simple as a hug, a few kind words of encouragement, or sharing your time with someone can go a long way. That's why we're asking you to join our campaign by using Facebook, Instagram or Twitter to share your STORIES, PICTURES and WORDS of ENCOURAGEMENT with us via #Alstroemeria and @JubileeProject, because Doing Good is Contagious.

title: Road Back Home | A Jubilee Project Fellowship Short Film
description:
Tweet: http://clicktotweet.com/3s10q | FB: http://on.fb.me/1aSDrok
This summer, Jubilee Project hosted a fellowship program inviting 13 filmmakers to live together and produce a short film in 10 days. They produced three short films that inspire change. This is Alstroemeria. Learn more about the fellowship here: www.jubileeproject.org/fellowship

Reunited with his kidnapped daughter after 10 years, a father must learn how to rebuild his relationship with her while battling the demons in his own life. Through their struggle, they find that healing is only possible when they find the vulnerability and courage to face the brokenness within.

This film was inspired by the true story of the kidnapping of 11 year old Jaycee Lee Dugard and other kidnap victims. While the media often covers the disappearance and discovery of abducted victims, its perspective is incomplete as most people don't realize the intense emotional and mental process victims and their families must go through to reintegrate into society. We hope our film will be able to spark discussion and awareness on this issue. We also hope this film empowers anyone who is facing dark times in their life to find the strength to keep moving forward.

This film was produced as part of the 2013 Jubilee Project Fellowship. JP fellows were tasked with writing, directing and editing films that inspire change, all within 10 days.

title: Catching Clouds | A Jubilee Project Film on Hepatitis B
description:
click to tweet: http://bit.ly/14J5mj0 | fb: http://on.fb.me/16kHdyI

This summer, Jubilee Project hosted a fellowship program inviting 13 filmmakers to live together and produce a short film in 10 days. They produced three short films that inspire change. This is Catching Clouds. Learn more about the fellowship here: www.jubileeproject.org/fellowship

Although obstacles may present themselves throughout our lives, it is how we decide to continue on that makes a difference. Catching Clouds is a story about people transforming the way they see themselves by enduring personal setbacks. 

We produced this short film in order to raise awareness for Hepatitis B, and to encourage viewers to live out their lives to the fullest. Hepatitis B is the most common infection of the liver, which can lead to premature death from cirrhosis, liver cancer, and liver failure. One in ten Asian Americans & Pacific Islanders are lifelong carriers of Hepatitis B. Sadly, most carriers do not know they are infected because there are no immediate symptoms even if your liver blood test comes out normal. The good news is that we can treat and prevent this disease if more people are aware of it.

Now it's your turn to take action: 
Share with us a story of when you were able to overcome something in your life that seemed impossible. Send your stories to us via Twitter, Instagram or Facebook with the hashtag #JPCatchingClouds @Jubilee Project

FB: http://on.fb.me/19j1vQp | Tweet: http://bit.ly/1bOT7cd

Located in the heart of Los Angeles, Skid Row is a 50-block community, where over 4,000 homeless people call their home. Considered one of the largest homeless populations in the country, Skid Row is typically a place where people go when they have nothing left. No job. No house. No money. Still, many continue to hold on to something that no economic recession or house foreclosure will ever take away: their dreams. Dreams of making something of their lives. Dreams of giving their child a better life than their own. Dreams of helping others who face the same problems they do. 

Jubilee Project spent a day in Skid Row asking the people on the streets one question: What is your Dream? What we found is that even though the homeless lack much in the material sense, they have found value in something deeper. Many have found hope in knowing that there is still purpose in their lives. And that even though they have little in the way of monetary wealth, they have so much more to offer those who need it the most. By living their dreams and helping others around them, they empower us to do the same. 

That's why we are starting a Jubilee Project Action Team, called jpX. Join this group to be a part of a movement of people around the world who are excited about making a difference in their own communities. jpX members will be responsible for taking part in a broader campaign to make tangible impact at the grassroots level. Learn more and apply here: http://www.jubileeproject.org/jpX.

title: Fireflies Behind the Scenes | Jubilee Project
description:
Watch Fireflies here: http://bit.ly/jpfireflies

Autism is an issue that is often misunderstood and stigmatized. We hope that "Fireflies" can raise awareness for Autism and encourage people to reach out to autistic individuals in their local communities. You can help us by participating in two ways!

1. The "Tweet Taylor Campaign"
Did you know that "Fireflies" was inspired by Taylor Swift's "You Belong with Me" music video? Can you imagine what would happen if Taylor Swift watched and tweeted about "Fireflies" to her 21 million followers? We need your help to make this happen!

After watching "Fireflies" tweet a message at Taylor like this one:

Hey @taylorswift13 we need your help! Please watch & tweet short film #Fireflies for #Autism awareness! http://bit.ly/JPFireflies

Make sure you include the link to the video, and hashtags #Fireflies and #autism. Donate one tweet a day from this Wednesday to Saturday (Dec 19th-22nd), to ask Taylor to help raise awareness for this important cause. With all of us working together, we are sure to catch her attention! Let's help 21 million people around the world learn about #autism!

2. "Autism Is..."
Do you know a friend, a relative, or stranger who is autistic? Have you been affected by autism? We would love to hear your story! If you answered no to either of the questions above but know someone who can answer yes, we encourage you to reach out and get to know that individual. Send us an email telling us your story and a picture of yourself with a sign that finishes the sentence, "Autism is..."

Please send us everything by January 10 to the email: dgic(at)jubileeproject.org. We look forward to reading your stories and collecting your photos of hope.

To learn more about autism and join the discussion, visit http://www.autisable.com/.

title: 12 Days of Kindness | Jubilee Project DGiC Campaign
description:
Tweet this vid: http://clicktotweet.com/84Tcb | FB http://on.fb.me/Qw1Equ | Join #12DOK Campaign: http://www.jubileeproject.org/12DOK

The Jubilee Project 12 Days of Kindness (#12DOK) is a campaign to inspire people to participate in simple acts of kindness. Throughout the month, we will take part in various activities that will help change the world. After each day, we'll ask you to facebook and tweet an image of you participating in this activity using the hashtags @JubileeProject and #12DOK. 

Learn more at: http://www.jubileeproject.org/12DOK

Special thanks to New Heights for their song "This is Christmas" (http://youtube.com/newheightsmusic)
--
The 12 Days:

Day 1 (Monday December 3): JP Day of Commitment: Change your facebook and twitter profile pictures to the #12DOK images, dowloaded here. Tweet and Facebook an encouraging message declaring your commitment to the @JubileeProject 12 Days of Kindness. Use the hashtag #12DOK, and include this link www.jubileeproject.org/12DOK. We're excited to follow your posts and stories as we journey together on this awesome ride.

Day 2: (Tuesday December 4): JP Day of Hope: Write a simple message of hope on a sticky note and place it in a public place for someone to find. Facebook, Instagram and Tweet a photo of your message using the hashtags @JubileeProject #12DOK #JPHope.

Day 3: (Wednesday December 5): JP Day of Fasting - Go hungry for one meal today and donate the money you would have used to buy food to an organization that serves the hungry. Facebook and Tweet about which organization you are supporting and why you are fasting to support them. Use the hashtags @JubileeProject #12DOK #JPFasting.

Day 4: (Friday December 7): JP Day of Love - Create an anonymous care package for someone who needs to know they are loved. The care package can include snacks, an encouraging note, photos and/or anything else you want to include to lift their spirits. Facebook, Instagram and Tweet a photo of your care package using the hashtags @JubileeProject #12DOK #JPLove.

Day 5: (Sunday December 9): JP Day of Rest: Spend the day laughing and not thinking about anything related to school or work. Do something that gives you energy and joy. Facebook, Instagram and Tweet a photo of your activity using hashtags @JubileeProject #12DOK #JPRest.

Day 6: (Tuesday December 11): JP Day of Creativity - We were given gifts so that we can bless others. We leave this day up to you, but we encourage you to use your gifts to make someone feel loved. But be creative and courageous! Facebook, Instagram and Tweet a photo of your activity using hashtags @JubileeProject #12DOK #JPCreativity

Day 7: (Thursday December 13): JP Day of Peace - Adversity between friends is like a disease that destructs joy. Think of someone who you need to reconcile with. Reach out to them and schedule a coffee, meal or phone call and spend the conversation being humble, open and honest. Facebook or Tweet a quote or lesson you learned in your conversation along with a photo with your friend if you are able to take one. Use hashtags @JubileeProject #12DOK #JPPeace.

Day 8: (Saturday December 15): JP Day of Encouragement - One word of encouragement will transform someone's day. Stand in a public area for an hour holding signs of encouragement to passing people or cars. Facebook, Instagram and Tweet a photo of your experience using hashtags @JubileeProject #12DOK #JPEncouragement.

Day 9: (Tuesday December 18): JP Day of Joy - Joy is meant to be experienced with others. How many people can you give a piece of joy to today? Spend the whole day hugging as many people as you can, and yes, even strangers. Facebook, Instagram and Tweet the number of people you hugged today along with a photo if you are able to take one. Use hashtags @JubileeProject #12DOK #JPJoy.

Day 10: (Thursday December 20): JP Day of Courage: A simple act of courage can change the world. Talk to a complete stranger today (but remember to be safe!). Spend the time learning their story and find ways to serve them in some way. Facebook and Tweet one lesson or quote you took away from that conversation, using that hashtags @JubileeProject #12DOK #JPCourage.

Day 11: (Saturday December 22): JP Day of Service - We are our greatest selves when we serve others. Spend the day at a food kitchen, homeless shelter or any volunteer center helping those who need your help. Facebook, Instagram and Tweet a photo of your experience using hashtags @JubileeProject #12DOK #JPService.

Day 12: (Saturday December 29): JP Day of Giving - It is a blessing to give to those who lack. Collect any clothes, books, toys and other things you may not need, and donate it to your local Goodwill or donation center. Facebook, Instagram and Tweet a photo of your donation using the hashtags @JubileeProject #12DOK #JPGiving.

The Jubilee Project's mission is not only to inspire you but also compel you to take action and do good in your community. With the two year anniversary of "Love Language" around the corner, we want to challenge you to get involved in a new series we're calling "DGiC". 

We want you and your friends to film yourselves going out into your community and leaving sticky notes of encouragement and inspiration for others to find. We believe that one simple note or encouragement can brighten someone's day or even change someone's life. Be creative! Think of cool messages you want to share and also interesting places to leave your notes (for example, in library books, on someone's rearview mirror, to ask someone to homecoming, or even fill someone's room up with post-it notes of encouragement!). Just make sure to film the process so that we can share it with everyone!

Important: when you shoot your DGiC video with a camera phone, PLEASE turn your phone camera sideways so that you are shooting the video in "Landscape" mode (ie. horizontally longer).

Please share all of your footage with Jubilee Project [project.jubilee (at) gmail.com] via Dropbox (http://www.dropbox.com) by October 30th!

Also, we want to celebrate the 2-year anniversary with a new Love Language t-shirt contest. Design and submit a t-shirt related to Love Language for a chance to win both a DGiC shirt and your newly designed shirt! All submissions should be emailed to LoveLanguage (at) jubileeproject.org by October 21st.

Don't Vote??? No, that's not it... #TakeAction. Make your voice heard! 

There are approximately 18 million Asians and Pacific Islanders in the United States and in 2008, only 55% of Asian American citizens of voting age registered to vote -  Yikes... 

18MillionRising is about you, your friends, your cousins, your aunties, your whole community. It's about making our voices heard...on Election Day. Visit our friends at http://bit.ly/18MRjubilee RIGHT NOW to register to vote. 

18MR is about us, all 18 million of us.

Produced for a campaign by the Jubilee Project and International Secret Agents (ISA).  In partnership with 18 Million Rising, an initiative to amplify Asian Pacific Islander American political voices and grow our movement.

Jubilee Project and ISA are raffling off three autographed "(Don't) VOTE" Scripts, autographed by everyone in the video. To win an autographed script: 1. Register to vote at http://bit.ly/18MRjubilee 2. Tweet your pledge to vote in the upcoming elections, and include in your tweet: "@JubileeProject @ISAtvOfficial #TakeAction 18mr.org" The Jubilee Project and ISA will choose three random winners to receive the signed scripts.

title: Dear Daniel | Jubilee Project Film
description:
Tweet: http://clicktotweet.com/dGEfp | FB: http://on.fb.me/U4MZUy
 
There are times in our lives when we wonder if we were meant to follow our passions and live for something greater. "Dear Daniel" is a coming of age story of a young man, John Lee, who is trying to chase his dreams. But to do so, he must face and confront the most important people in his life. In the end, only he can choose the path he wishes to take.
 
Our goal with Dear Daniel is to empower young people who watch this film to chase their own dreams and live a life of passion. Too often we settle for less because of the many factors that tell us we need to play it safe and take the more conventional route. But this keeps us from actually becoming the person we are meant to be.
 
Now, we'd love to hear from you. In an essay, short story or poem, tell us about your passion and why it's worth fighting for. We'll pick the most thoughtful and inspiring essay and send the writer a free Jubilee Project Doing Good is Contagious T-Shirt. We'll also set up a Google hangout between the Jubilee Project boys and the winner to discuss your stories, and share insights and mentorship on navigating this often daunting road to finding your life's purpose. Submit your essay to us be emailing us at project.jubilee(at)gmail(dot)com by October 8, 2012. http://jubileeproject.org/2012/09/17/new-film-essay-contest-dear-daniel/

title: "End of AIDS" | Jubilee Project Film Fundraiser
description:
Join the Jubilee Project to create a film that can help end of AIDS. Please support us and donate here: http://jubileeproject.causevox.com/

For the first time ever, we are on the brink of the end of AIDS. However, reaching that tipping point depends on you.

"End of AIDS" is a 25-minute film that is a call to action and centerpiece for a social media campaign to end AIDS. Partnering with established AIDS organizations including Partners in Health and Health GAP, this film will be released in time for World AIDS Day 2012 in December.

While most individuals understand the severity of the AIDS epidemic, many are unaware of the recent strides in treatment and prevention. While treatments exist and the path to successfully ending AIDS has been identified, this message and information needs to be synthesized in a narrative that is compelling and interesting for the average individual. 

We believe that a compelling social media campaign focused on the end of AIDS can bring this global epidemic back to the forefront of the public conversation, provide a common message for existing organizations to coalesce around, and ultimately lead to renewed commitments from governments, donors, and the private sector.

title: Behind the Scenes: The Making of "Back to Innocence"
description:
The Jubilee Project produced "Back to Innocence" to give voice to the millions of children who are forced and manipulated into sex trafficking every year. This video is an inside look at how this short film was created and the thought process and reasoning behind the concept.

To read more information about the making of "Back to Innocence," check out the director's commentary: http://jubileeproject.org/?p=2287

To watch "Back to Innocence," click here: http://bit.ly/backtoinnocence

By watching this film, you have been given an opportunity to be a voice in your community. Use it. When you share this film with others, let it be a tool to help empower them: hold meetings, organize events, and initiate simple conversations around this issue. Your voice matters in helping to combat this injustice. 

Additionally, become a donor to directly help non-profit organizations combat sex trafficking. Through this film, we are partnering with an organization called Odanadi to help them continue to help victims in need. All of the proceeds will go directly to helping the organization end trafficking around the world. To learn more about their organization or to make a donation to them, please go to http://www.odanadi.org.

Finally, stay connected to the Jubilee Project. This is just the beginning of our efforts to shine a bright light on this darkness. We believe that films play a powerful role in combating this issue. To produce these films, we'll need your continual support and prayers. To follow us, you can:

description:

Join us to celebrate Generosity Day: http://www.spreadgenerosity.com

The Jubilee Project is celebrating Valentine's Day as Generosity Day, a day of sharing love with everyone. Let's make the day about love, action and human connection, because we can do more than just cards, chocolates and flowers. 

There are many ways you can celebrate Generosity Day. One way is to pledge to say YES to everything. You can say YES to the homeless person asking for change, you can say YES without being asked (putting dishes in the dishwasher), you can say YES by looking someone in the eye and smiling, and you can say YES by asking how someone's day was. 

By promising for just one day to say YES to everything, we can create a ripple effect of kindness, make a difference in our communities, and just might brighten someone's day. 

Join us and spread the word. Pledge your support with others around the world: http://causes.com/generosityday

title: Our Voices: Type 2 Diabetes
description:
Tweet: http://clicktotweet.com/ayg7P Facebook: http://on.fb.me/nLmagX 

"Our Voices" is a video series that gives a voice to the voiceless. Join the Jubilee Project as we tackle type 2 diabetes, often termed the "silent killer" because of its chronic but deadly nature.

Watch and share this video to help us raise awareness for diabetes. You may also become a sponsor by emailing us (project.jubilee@gmail.com) and pledging to donate a penny per view to the Union Square Family Health Center in Somerville, MA for their innovative diabetes initiatives.

Type 2 diabetes is a chronic illness that causes high blood sugar resulting from insulin resistance. It represents one of the largest global burden of disease, affecting 350 million people globally and 1 out of 4 Americans. Diabetes is often correlated with issues of lifestyle, such as diet and exercise, and is also prevalent in low and middle income countries where more than 80% of diabetes deaths occur.

Directed and edited by Eric I. Lu
Produced with Dr. Andrew Ellner, Eddie Lee, Jason Y. Lee
"Main theme" music by Jesse Chui & Henry Tsai from the film "At Musing's End" by Wong Fu Productions
"Dream" music by Priscilla Ahn
Special thanks to the patients and staff in the Phyllis Jen Center for Primary Care at the Brigham and Women's Hospital, Harvard Center for Primary Care & Primary Care Progress

title: What's Your Story?
description:
You are our inspiration. The reason we are driven to making a difference in the world is you, and your stories. So we are excited to launch this video challenge with the White House.

Share your three-minute story about any cause that is important to you, whether it's education, the arts, public service, etc. Make a video (or an essay) about why this cause matters to you and what you are doing to make the world around you a better place. 

After reviewing your videos, the White House will invite three of you and your guest to the White House to share your stories with White House leaders. Entries should be submitted online at www.whitehouse.gov/whatsyourstory by Tuesday, November 1st, 2011. 

Your video can be in any form (music video, video blog, interview, etc). Be creative, Be inspirational, Be you! Remember, doing good is contagious. 

If you have a question, email us at project.jubilee@gmail.com

title: Days in Africa #2: One in Five
description:
The Jubilee Project "Days in Africa" series is a glimpse of the lessons, stories and adventures we're experiencing during our time in Africa. In Lusaka, Zambia, where Jason is living the HIV percentage is nearly 20% meaning that about one in five people have the disease. We hope that you'll join us in learning more about this serious disease and fighting back. 

HIV/AIDS is a serious disease that has claimed millions of lives for several decades. While there is no cure, the development of Antiretroviral drugs has reduced the mortality and severity of the disease. Unfortunately, lack of funding for ARV drugs and limited HIV testing has allowed this epidemic to continue spreading particularly in African countries. 

To learn more about the issue and find out how you can take action, here are some organizations you can check out:
Health Gap - http://www.healthgap.org/
Student Global AIDS Campaign - http://www.studentglobalaidscampaign.org/

title: Jubilee Project Spotlight: Hines Ward Tackles Bullying
description:
NFL wide receiver Hines Ward is a force to be reckoned with on the field. His hard-hitting and hard working attitude has earned him the coveted MVP honor in Superbowl XL. Yet, it's his story off the field that inspires us all. 

Growing up, Hines Ward was picked on for being different. As a half-Korean, half-black child, he never felt like he really belonged. He felt the humiliation of being bullied every single day, and it was only through football that he learned to cope with the teasing. As an NFL player and a newly sworn-in commissioner on the White House Initiative on Asian Americans and Pacific Islanders, he has made it his mission to fight bullying.

He started his own foundation called The Hines Ward Helping Hands Foundation to help biracial kids who are bullied. Learn more about his foundation here: http://www.hinesward.com/helping-hands-foundation.php

We also want to congratulate Hines for winning Dancing With The Stars 2011.

This is part of a series called Jubilee Project Spotlight to shine a light on ordinary people doing extraordinary things. Watch more videos at www.youtube.com/jubileeproject

title: World Without Moms
description:
Jubilee Project made this video to honor moms around the world because we were inspired by the love and care we received from our own moms.

Moms mean a lot to all of us. Yet, every year 7 million women are injured and 350,000 women die from complications due to childbirth. These deaths, however, are preventable by providing basic maternal health care. 

For every view that we get on this video, Jubilee Project sponsors will donate a penny to Every Mother Counts, an organization dedicated to improving maternal health in developing countries. Together, let's help build a world where children won't have to live without moms.

You can help moms in a few ways:

1. Share this video with your friends and of course your mom to let her know how much she means to you.

2. Become a sponsor of the video and pledge to donate a penny per view to Every Mother Counts. Email project.jubilee@gmail.com to sign up.

3. Visit Every Mother Counts to learn more about this issue and see how you can get involved: http://www.everymothercounts.org

*This video was awarded "Best Video" for Acumen Fund's Search for the Obvious "Moms Matter" Challenge. To see other submissions and learn more about maternal health, go to http://searchfortheobvious.com/savemoms

description:
Relationships don't always have a fairytale ending. This is a music video about love's inevitable let downs. It's also a story about love that is unconditional; despite the bitter realities it faces, love is patient, love is kind, and love always perseveres. Produced in tribute to the korean dramas we grew up watching on warm summer mornings. 

The Jubilee Project produced this video to raise awareness and money for HepB Free (sfhepbfree.org). Three ways to help them fight this disease:
- Spread the love. Every time this video is viewed in the month of April, sponsors will each donate a penny to the organization. 
- Become a sponsor by emailing project.jubilee@gmail.com and pledge to donate 1 penny per view in the month of April (remember, you can cap your donation).
- Download the song for a donation of your choice at http://jubileeproject.bandcamp.com. 
All proceeds from this fundraiser will go to HepB Free to help them raise awareness about this disease, which affects 1 in 10 Asian Americans and Pacific Islanders.

title: "Beautiful" Teaser: Please Sponsor to help Becky's Fund
description:
Love is a beautiful thing. This is a teaser video to our February fundraiser video, called "Beautiful." This Valentine's Day, tell the one you love how special they are by sending them this video and helping a great cause. The video "Beautiful" will come out on February 7th, so please subscribe to be the first to watch it.

This fundraiser video will support Becky's Fund, a non-profit organization whose mission is to raise awareness and prevent domestic violence. This organization was started by Becky Lee, who has fought to empower women and educate the community on this issue. You can help this organization by becoming a sponsor, or by simply watching the video!

This is how the fundraiser works. If you would like to support the cause financially, you can sign up to become a sponsor of the video, called "Beautiful," which will come out on February 7th. Each sponsor will pledge to donate 1 penny (or more) for each view the video receives in the month of February. So if the video ultimately receives 1500 views by the end of the month, each donor will donate $15. If the video receives 3000 views, each donor will donate $30, and so forth. The sponsor can also choose to cap the amount they donate, but we ask that they make this clear when they first sign up to become a sponsor. You can sign up to sponsor the video by emailing project.jubilee@gmail.com and including "Beautiful Video Sponsor" in the subject line. title: Jubilee Project Spotlight: Quarterback Donovan McNabb on Diabetes
description:
Washington Redskins Quarterback Donovan McNabb has long been an advocate for youth with diabetes. In fact, he started his own foundation to help kids combat this disease. Each year the American Diabetes Association (www.stopdiabetes.com) hosts the Donovan McNabb Diabetes Camp for Kids through the foundation's funding. title: What is your biggest regret in life?
description:
To make the world a better place, we must first become better ourselves. The new year gives us all a chance to turn a new leaf on our lives - a chance to start over, to wipe the slate clean. Too often, we live our lives without reflecting on the lessons we've learned and about the person we strive to become. We produced this video to encourage you to take some time in your life and think about these questions. What kind of life do you want to live?

This video was produced as part of our monthly fundraiser video series. The group we are supporting for this fundraiser is Services for the UnderServed (SUS), an organization that provides necessary mental and physical services for the neglected and needy. More than medicine, these patients need a second chance at life and the resources to pick themselves up again. Founded in 1978, Services for the UnderServed (SUS) has gained a reputation for helping individuals and families faced with a wide range of challenges‚Äîmental illness, developmental disability, physical disability, AIDS, homelessness, unemployment and poverty. Through their dedication to this cause, thousands of patients have been able to turn their own leaves on life and start anew.

This is how you can help Services for the Underserved:
1. Email project.jubilee@gmail.com to become a sponsor of this video. By signing up to sponsor the video you will donate 1 penny per view that the video receives in January. So if this video is watched a hundred times in the month, sponsors will each donate 1 dollar, and so forth. Remember that you can put a cap on how much you donate. Just let us know in your email how much you want to cap your donation at.
2. By simply watching the video you can help the cause. Each time you or your friends watch the video, a certain amount of money will be donated depending on how many sponsors we get. So if there are 5 sponsors, each view will generate 5 cents for the cause.

The video was inspired and produced with the consent of 50 People, 1 Question (50p1q.com). Music was produced by and used with the permission of Jesse Chui and David Lanz

title: Sound the Call for World AIDS Day
description:
Produced by:
Eric I. Lu

The Jubilee Project made this video featuring Dr. Paul Farmer, co-founder of Partners In Health, to raise awareness for World AIDS Day.

This World AIDS Day on December 1, 2010, join us as we rally to increase global AIDS funding. Global AIDS funding has flat-lined and consequently many programs and efforts to help those living with HIV/AIDS have been negatively affected. Increased, sustained commitment from places like the United States is important not only to provide continual care to these millions around the world but also to provide health care in general to those living without it. We have learned that more funding for HIV/AIDS has translated to a stronger health care system for people in poverty and underserved areas.

Here are 3 things you can do on World AIDS Day to raise awareness for this important cause.

1. If you're in Boston, come join us from 7-9pm in Boston Common for a rally and vigil. The goal is to get 1000 people out, and there will be performances and speakers! For those of you not in Boston, you can find out an event near you at http://www.takeanumber.org.

2. Studies have shown that hand-written letters are effective ways to make your voice heard. Write a letter and call your local Senator asking them to take leadership on this issue. You can go here to find out how you can contact your senator: http://www.senate.gov/reference/common/faq/How_to_contact_senators.htm

3. Share this video with your family, friends, and colleagues. Talk to them about why this issue is important and why now is a crucial time to be taking action.

To learn more about this issue, you can check out the following articles:

Desmond Tutu: Op-ed in New York Times
http://www.nytimes.com/2010/07/21/opinion/21tutu.html

Student Letter to President Obama
http://www.studentglobalaidscampaign.org/2010/09/student-letter-to-president-obama.html

Health Gap
http://www.healthgap.org/press/global_fund_pledge.htm

Acknowledgements:
The Jubilee Project is an organization that makes videos for a good cause. Part of our missions is to advocate for those in need. Go to http://www.jubileeproject.org to learn more. 

We would like to thank Dr. Paul Farmer and Partners In Health for the photographs. Special thanks also go out to all those who helped make this video possible: Matt B., Matt G., Ben, Margie, Salman, John, Arjun, Nworah, Rumbi, Krishna, Charles, Jon, Leslie, Emily, Eddie, Jason, and Elaine.

We also want to credit the WHO for the statistics shown in this video, as well as change.gov, dailymail.co.uk, CNN, and the Associated Press for their footage from Youtube.

Finally the use of the South Africa National Anthem is in no way suggestive that HIV/AIDS is only an Africa problem, but rather it is used because it's a beautiful song that is symbolic of unity, perseverance, and reconciliation.

title: Jubilee Project Spotlight: Myron Rolle - Scholar, Athlete, Philanthropist
description:
As the 2010 NFL season begins, this Jubilee Project Spotlight features Tennessee Titan Safety Myron Rolle. Myron was never a typical athlete. He would spend the time between practices reading books and talking to professors. He stayed up late at night studying for the next biology exam while watching game films to prepare for the next game. He was forced to juggle his many passions, but that's what he did best. Because of his hard work and persistence, his story is unique: he is a Rhodes Scholar and now an NFL player, being only the third player in NFL history to accomplish this feat.

But that's not why we're featuring him. It's what he plans to do with this excellent opportunity that makes him shine in this Jubilee Project Spotlight. After college, he started the Myron Rolle Foundation, dedicated to the support of health, wellness, educational and other charitable initiatives throughout the world that benefit children and families in need. Through this foundation, he has directed the Myron Rolle Wellness and Leadership Academy and the My Way to Health Program.

After the NFL, Myron plans to go to Medical School to become a neurosurgeon. He is currently building the Myron Rolle Medical Clinic, which will provide much-needed health services to residents of Exuma, Bahamas as well as state-of-the-art wellness and training facilities for athletes and visitors.

It is clear that Myron is a gifted man. But what makes him stand apart from the rest is his tenacity and courage to inspire those around him by sharing these gifts with the world.

The mission of Jubilee Project Spotlight is to shine a light on people and organizations who are doing inspiring work to better the world around them. Go to www.youtube.com/jubileeproject to see more videos.
